"Mäkipää R., Karjalainen T., Pussinen A., Kellomäki S.","Effects of climate change and nitrogen deposition on the carbon sequestration of a forest ecosystem in the boreal zone",1999,"Canadian Journal of Forest Research","29","10",,"1490","1501",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033306490&partnerID=40&md5=0f873707894334bc32cce5d60c973c7f","Finnish Forest Research Institute, Unioninkatu 40A, FIN-00170 Helsinki, Finland; European Forest Institute, Torikatu 34, FIN-80100 Joensuu, Finland; Faculty of Forestry, University of Joensuu, P.O. Box 111, FIN-80101 Joensuu, Finland","Mäkipää, R., Finnish Forest Research Institute, Unioninkatu 40A, FIN-00170 Helsinki, Finland; Karjalainen, T., European Forest Institute, Torikatu 34, FIN-80100 Joensuu, Finland; Pussinen, A., European Forest Institute, Torikatu 34, FIN-80100 Joensuu, Finland; Kellomäki, S., Faculty of Forestry, University of Joensuu, P.O. Box 111, FIN-80101 Joensuu, Finland","Global warming and nitrogen deposition are expected to modify the carbon sequestration of boreal forests, causing feedback to atmospheric CO2 and climate. The objective of this study was to assess the effects of climate change and various N deposition rates on C sequestration of a forest ecosystem. The study uses a gap-type forest model for a managed Scots pine (Pinus sylvestris L.) stand in conditions representing southern Finland. Model computations indicated that, for both current and changed (+4°C and + 10% in precipitation) climatic conditions, increased levels of N deposition from 6 to 12 kg·ha-1 per year increased C uptake by 4-6.5%. Total C stock (vegetation, litter, and soil organic matter) was 11% higher for current level of N deposition than without deposition. Changed climate resulted in a 10% higher C stock of the vegetation but 30% lower C stock in the forest soil. Consequently, the total C stock in forests was decreased because of the greater decline in soil C stock. The combined effects of climate change and N deposition decreased the average C stock of forest (over a 100-year rotation period) with annual depodition rates under 12 kg N·ha-1 but slightly increased C stock with deposition of 24 kg N·ha-1.",,"atmospheric deposition; boreal forest; carbon sequestration; climate change; forest ecosystem; nitrogen; Finland; Pinus sylvestris",,,,,,"Aber, J.D., Nadelhoffer, K.J., Steudler, P., Melillo, J.M., Nitrogen saturation in northern forest ecosystems. Excess nitrogen from fossil fuel combustion may stress the biosphere (1989) BioScience, 39, pp. 378-386; Apps, M.J., Kurz, W.A., Luxmoore, R.J., Nilsson, L.O., Sedjo, R.A., Schmidt, R., Simpson, L.G., Vinson, T.S., Boreal forests and tundra (1993) Water Air Soil Pollut., 70, pp. 39-53; Beier, C., Gundersen, P., Hansen, K., Rasmussen, L., Experimental manipulation of water and nutrient input to a Norway spruce plantation at Klosterhede, Denmark. II. Effects on tree growth and nutrition (1995) Plant Soil, 168-169, pp. 613-622; Berg, B., Nutrient release from litter and humus in coniferous forest soils - A mini review (1986) Scand. J. For. Res., 1, pp. 359-369; Berg, B., McClaugherty, C., De Santo, A.V., Johansson, M.-B., Ekbohm, G., Decomposition of litter and soil organic matter - Can we distinguish a mechanism for soil organic matter buildup? (1995) Scand. J. For. Res., 10, pp. 108-119; Box, G.E.P., Lucas, H.L., Design of experiments in nonlinear situations (1959) Biometrica, 47, pp. 77-99; Cajander, A.K., Forest types and their significance (1949) Acta For. Fenn. No. 56, 56, pp. 1-71; Cannell, M.G.R., (1982) World Forest Biomass and Primary Production Data, , Academic Press, London; Cannell, M.G.R., Dewar, R.C., The carbon sink provided by plantation forests and their products in Britain (1995) Forestry, 68, pp. 35-48; Cao, M., Woodward, F.I., Dynamic responses of terrestrial ecosystem carbon cycling to global climate change (1998) Nature (London), 393, pp. 249-252; Carter, T., Posch, M., Tuomenvirta, H., (1995) SILMUSCE